a]]\n* [[Romantic drama]]\n}}\n| creator = {{Plain list|\n* Laurie McCarthy\n* [[Stephanie SenGupta]]\n}}\n| starring = {{Plain list|\n* [[Adelaide Kane]]\n* [[Megan Follows]]\n* [[Torrance Coombs]] \n* [[Toby Regbo]]\n* [[Jenessa Grant]]\n* Celina Sinden\n* [[Caitlin Stasey]]\n* [[Anna Popplewell]]\n* [[Alan van Sprang]]\n* [[Jonathan Keltz]]\n* [[Sean Teale]]\n* [[Craig Parker]]\n* [[Rose Williams (actress)|Rose Williams]]\n* [[Rachel Skarsten]]\n* Charlie Carrick\n* [[Ben Geurens]]\n* Spencer MacPherson\n* [[Dan Jeannotte]]\n* Jonathan Goad\n* [[Will Kemp (actor, born 1977)|Will Kemp]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme = \"Scotland\" by [[The Lumineers]]\n| composer = [[Trevor Morris (musician)|Trevor Morris]]\n| country = {{Plain list|\n* United States\n* Canada\n}}\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 4\n| num_episodes = 78\n| list_episodes = List of Reign episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plain list|\n* Laurie McCarthy\n* [[Stephanie SenGupta]]\n* [[Brad Silberling]]\n* John Weber\n* Frank Siracusa}}\n| producer =\n| location =\n| camera =\n| runtime = 42 minutes\n| company = {{Plain list|\n* Joyful Girl Productions\n* Take 5 Productions\n* Whizbang Films\n* [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n* [[CBS Television Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor = {{Plain list|\n* [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n}}\n| network = [[The CW]]\n| picture_format = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Digital|Dolby Digital 5.1]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2013|10|17}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2017|6|16}}\n| website = http://www.cwtv.com/shows/reign/\n| website_title = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''Reign''''' is an American [[historical drama|historical]] [[romantic drama]] television series following the early exploits of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. The series, created by [[Stephanie SenGupta]] and Laurie McCarthy, premiered on October 17, 2013, on [[The CW]],<ref name=\"ewanounce\">{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/05/09/cw-sci-fi-shows/ | title=CW orders 3 new sci-fi shows | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | date=May 9, 2013 | accessdate=May 10, 2013 | author=James Hibberd}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/cws-the-tomorrow-people-the-100-ordered-to-series/ | title=UPDATE: CW's 'The Tomorrow People', 'The 100', 'Reign' & 'Oxygen' Ordered To Series | website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] | date=May 9, 2013 | accessdate=May 10, 2013 | author=Nellie Andreeva}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/carrie-diaries-cw-nikita-tomorrow-people-1200478752/ | title=CW Orders 4 Dramas; Renews 'Carrie Diaries,' 'Nikita' | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=May 9, 2013 | accessdate=May 10, 2013 | author=Cynthia Littleton}}</ref> and concluded after four seasons on June 16, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2016/03/11/the-flash-the-100-and-even-crazy-ex-girlfriend-renewed-all-11-cw-series-picked-up-for-2016-17/|title='The Flash', 'The 100' and even 'Crazy Ex-Girlfriend' renewed: All CW series picked up for 2016\u201317|last=Porter|first=Rick|work=TV by the Numbers|date=March 11, 2016|accessdate=March 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/11/16/cw-midseason-2017-premiere-dates|title=CW sets Riverdale premiere date; Supernatural, Legends of Tomorrow moving timeslots|last=Abrams|first=Natalie|publisher=EW|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/reign-canceled-end-four-seasons-the-cw-1201866273/|title=\u2018Reign\u2019 To End After 4 Seasons On the CW|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=December 7, 2016|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{further|List of Reign episodes}}\n{{:List of Reign episodes}}\nThe highly fictionalized series follows the early exploits of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. The first season opens in 1557, with Mary living in a convent in France, but she is quickly returned to the castle where we learn she is awaiting her marriage to [[Francis II of France|Prince Francis]], to whom she has been engaged since they were six. Mary has to contend with changing politics and power plays, as well as her burgeoning feelings for Francis and the romantic attentions of Francis's bastard half-brother, Bash. Francis's mother, [[Catherine de' Medici]], secretly tries to prevent the marriage following [[Nostradamus]]'s confidential prediction that the marriage will lead to Francis's death. The series also follows the affairs of Mary's Scottish handmaidens Kenna, Aylee, Lola, and Greer, who are searching for husbands of their own at French Court.\n\nThe second season opens after the death of [[Henry II of France|King Henry II]], and follows the rise of Francis and Mary as King and Queen of France and Scotland. Together they have to balance their marriage with their roles as monarchs, and deal with the rising religious conflict between [[French Wars of Religion|Catholics and Protestants]], as well as the ambitions of the rival [[House of Bourbon]] for the throne of France.\n\nThe third season follows Francis's declining health and his death partway through the season, leaving Mary a widow and struggling to find new footing since she's no longer bound to France as its queen. Francis's brother [[Charles IX of France|Charles]] is crowned the new underaged king, with Catherine as regent. The third season also introduces the court of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth of England]], who plots against Mary, fends off marital prospects, and deals with her secret love affair with [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley]].\n\nThe fourth and final season has Mary returned to Scotland and trying to regain power in her homeland. She has to manage her allies, such as her bastard half-brother [[James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray|James]] and the outspoken [[James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell|Lord Bothwell]], as well as her enemies, such as the Protestant preacher [[John Knox]]. Tensions mount between Mary and Elizabeth, with Mary marrying [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley|Lord Darnley]], an English Catholic claimant to the English throne, in the hopes of taking England. In France, Catherine has to protect her son, [[Charles IX of France|King Charles IX]], from the ambitions of her daughter [[Elisabeth of Valois|Queen Leeza of Spain]] and her younger son, [[Henry III of France|Henry]].\n\n==Cast and characters==\n<!--Do not convert the prose list to a cast table, there is no support for this format \u2013 see Talk page -->\n\n===Main===\n* [[Adelaide Kane]] as [[Mary Stuart, Queen of Scots]]\n* [[Megan Follows]] as [[Catherine de' Medici]]\n* Celina Sinden as Greer of [[Kinross-shire|Kinross]]\n* [[Toby Regbo]] as [[Francis II of France]]<ref group=lower-alpha>Toby Regbo was credited as main cast through the fifth episode of season 3, and for the series finale.</ref>\n* [[Torrance Coombs]] as Sebastian \"Bash\" de Poitiers (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Anna Popplewell]] as Lady Lola (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Caitlin Stasey]] as Lady Kenna (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Alan van Sprang]] as [[Henry II of France]] (main season 1; recurring season 2)\n* [[Jenessa Grant]] as Lady Aylee (season 1)<ref group=lower-alpha>Jenessa Grant was credited as main cast until the eighth episode of season 1.</ref>\n* [[Jonathan Keltz]] as Leith Bayard (recurring season 1; main seasons 2\u20134)<ref group=lower-alpha>Jonathan Keltz was credited as main cast until the sixth episode of season 4.</ref>\n* [[Craig Parker]] as St\u00e9phane Narcisse (seasons 2\u20134)\n* [[Rose Williams (actress)|Rose Williams]] as [[Claude of France (1547\u20131575)|Claude of France]] (seasons 2\u20134)\n* [[Sean Teale]] as [[Louis, Prince of Cond\u00e9 (1530\u20131569)|Louis, Prince of Cond\u00e9]] (season 2)\n* [[Rachel Skarsten]] as [[Elizabeth I of England]] (guest season 2; main seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Ben Geurens]] as Gideon Blackburn (seasons 3\u20134)\n* Charlie Carrick as [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley]] (season 3)\n* Spencer MacPherson as [[Charles IX of France]] (recurring seasons 1,3; main season 4)<ref group=lower-alpha>The role was previously portrayed by Peter DaCunha in season 1.</ref>\n* [[Dan Jeannotte]] as [[James Stuart, 1st Earl of Moray|James Stewart]] (recurring season 3; main season 4)\n* Jonathan Goad as [[John Knox]] (recurring season 3; main season 4)\n* [[Will Kemp (actor)|Will Kemp]] as [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley|Darnley]] (season 4)\n<!--Do not convert the prose list to a cast table, there is no support for this format \u2013 see Talk page -->\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Rossif Sutherland]] as [[Nostradamus]] (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Anastasia Phillips]] as [[Elisabeth of Valois|Leeza of Spain]] (guest seasons 1; season 4)<ref group=lower-alpha>The role was previously portrayed by Caoimhe O'Malley in season 1.</ref>\n* [[Amy Brenneman]] as [[Mary of Guise|Marie de Guise]] (seasons 1\u20133)\n* Nick Slater as [[Henry III of France|Henri of Valois]] (guest seasons 1,3; season 4)<ref group=lower-alpha>The role was previously portrayed by Jackson Hodge-Carter in season 1 and Tomaso Sanelli in season 3.</ref>\n* [[Michael Therriault]] as Aloysius Castleroy (seasons 1\u20132; guest seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Anna Walton]] as [[Diane de Poitiers]] (season 1; guest season 2)\n* [[Katie Boland]] as Clarissa (season 1; guest season 2)\n* Gil Darnell as Christian, [[Francis, Duke of Guise|Duke of Guise]] (season 1; guest season 2)\n* [[Yael Grobglas]] as Olivia D'Amencourt (season 1)\n* [[Kathryn Prescott]] as Penelope (season 1)\n* [[Giacomo Gianniotti]] as \"Lord Julien\"/Remy (season 1)\n* [[Alexandra Ordolis]] as Delphine (seasons 2\u20133)\n* [[Ben Aldridge (actor)|Ben Aldridge]] as [[Antoine of Navarre]] (season 2; guest season 3)\n* Vince Nappo as Renaude (season 2)\n* [[Mark Ghanim\u00e9]] as [[Carlos, Prince of Asturias|Don Carlos of Spain]] (season 3; guest season 4)\n* Clara Pasieka as [[Amy Robsart|Amy Dudley]] (season 3)\n* [[Tom Everett Scott]] as [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William]] (season 3)\n* [[Nick Lee]] as Nicholas (season 3)\n* Nathaniel Middleton as Christophe (season 3)\n* Nola Augustson as [[Margaret Douglas|Lady Lennox]] (season 4)\n* [[Steve Lund]] as Luc Narcisse (season 4)\n* [[Adam Croasdell]] as [[James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell|Bothwell]] (season 4)\n<!--Do not convert the prose list to a cast table, there is no consensus support for this format here -->\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Conception===\nIn February 2013, [[The CW]] announced its order of a pilot for a TV series based on the life of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], created by [[Stephanie Sengupta]] and Laurie McCarthy, and produced by CBS Studios.<ref>{{ cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/02/alex-graves-bharat-nalluri-brad-silberling-to-direct-cw-pilots/|title=Alex Graves, Bharat Nalluri & Brad Silberling To Direct CW Pilots|date=February 24, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013|website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref> Part of the reason McCarthy chose Mary Stuart as the subject is because of her life history and multiple husbands, which makes her story \"sexier\".<ref>{{ cite web | first=An | last=Nicholson | title=Interviewing CW's 'Reign' Cast And Executive Producer | url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/An_Nicholson/2013/10/28/interviewing_cws_reign_cast_and_execut | publisher=StarPulse.com | date=October 28, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2014 }}</ref> The pilot was directed by [[Brad Silberling]], with Sengupta and McCarthy as the writers and executive directors; Sengupta left the team in May 2013, leaving Laurie McCarthy as the sole showrunner.<ref>{{ cite web|title='Reign' Co-Creator Stephanie SenGupta Exits|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/05/reign-co-creator-stephanie-sengupta-exits/|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 23, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013 }}</ref> On February 9, 2013, it was announced that Australian actress [[Adelaide Kane]] would be playing the main character.<ref>{{ cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/02/the-cw-casts-its-mary-queen-of-scots/|title=The CW Casts Its Mary Queen of Scots|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 9, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn interviews preceding the premiere, showrunner McCarthy described the show as deliberately taking liberties with history, and that it's more \"entertainment\" than history,<ref name=\"deadlinetour\" /> while actress [[Anna Popplewell]] referred to the show as \"fantasy history\", exploring the characters in hypothetical situations.<ref>{{ cite web|first=Andy|last=Swift|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2013/10/18/mary-queen-of-scots-historically-accurate-reign-cw/|title=Mary Queen of Scots: 'Reign' Stars Separate Historical Fact From Fiction|publisher=Hollywood Life|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> Actress Megan Follows described the show as \"''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'' for the pre-Renaissance\", as the show tends to extend historical events over a longer period of time.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Denise | last=Martin | title=Megan Follows on Anne of Green Gables and Her Racy New CW Series, Reign | url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/10/megan-follows-on-reign-anne-green-gables.html | publisher=Vulture.com |date=October 10, 2013 | accessdate=December 7, 2014 }}</ref> McCarthy added that the show is designed to be interesting to a contemporary audience, so viewers who aren't familiar with history will be able to watch and relate to the characters.<ref name=\"nydaily\">{{ cite web|first=David|last=Hinckley|title='Reign,' a prime-time soap about Mary, Queen of Scots, is a royal departure for CW |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/reign-royal-departure-cw-article-1.1413166|date=July 30, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013|work=Daily News|location=New York }}</ref> Among the creative choices is the use of modern music in the show soundtrack, and its costumes.<ref name=\"nydaily\" /> The show's costumes are designed by Meredith Markworth-Pollack, who worked on the CW's other shows ''[[Hart of Dixie]]'' and ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', who created different looks for Mary and her ladies, each to complement their differing personalities.<ref>{{ cite web |last=Bricker|first=Tierney|title=All Hail Reign's Fashion! The CW Hit's Costume Designer Breaks Down Mary and Her Ladies-in-Waiting's Looks|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/484037/all-hail-reign-s-fashion-the-cw-hit-s-costume-designer-breaks-down-mary-and-her-ladies-in-waiting-s-looks|publisher=E!|date=November 22, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> The ladies: Lola, Kenna, Greer, and Aylee, are loosely based on [[Mary Beaton]], [[Mary Seton]], [[Mary Fleming]], and [[Mary Livingston]] who were [[Lady-in-waiting|ladies-in-waiting]] to [[Mary, Queen of Scots]].\n\n===Casting===\nKane auditioned when she was filming a recurring role on the third season of MTV TV series ''[[Teen Wolf (2011 TV series)|Teen Wolf]]''. When Kane got the part, the ''Teen Wolf'' writers wrote her character off the show.<ref>{{cite web|last=Radish|first=Christina|title=Adelaide Kane Talks REIGN, How She Joined the Series, How the Role Affects Her Part on TEEN WOLF, and Her Character's Sense of Duty and Loyalty|website=Collider.com|url=https://collider.com/adelaide-kane-reign-interview/|date=October 10, 2013|accessdate=December 19, 2013}}</ref> Kane is part Scottish on both her mother and father's sides, and is possibly a descendant of the real [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] through her mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parade.com/200474/jasonlynch/reigns-adelaide-kane-takes-on-mary-queen-of-scots-its-fun-not-the-history-channel/|title=Reign's Adelaide Kane Takes on Mary, Queen of Scots: 'It's Fun \u2014 Not the History Channel!'|author=Jason Lynch|date=|work=Parade}}</ref> Kane did research on the historical Mary Stuart in preparing for the role.<ref name=\"deadlinetour\">{{ cite web | first=Lisa|last=De Moraes|title=TCA: CW's First Crunchy-Gravel Drama 'Reign' Flirts With History|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/07/tca-cws-first-crunchy-gravel-drama-flirts-with-history/ | website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 30, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> Toby Regbo was cast as Dauphin Francis before March 1, 2013, and British newcomer Celina Sinden was cast as Mary's lady-in-waiting Greer on that date.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Nellie | last=Andreeva | title=CW's 'Tomorrow People' & 'Reign' Cast Duo | url=https://deadline.com/2013/03/cws-tomorrow-people-reign-cast-duo-444280/ | website=Deadline Hollywood | date=March 1, 2013 |accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> Torrance Coombs was announced as having been cast as Sebastian, one of the leading characters, in March 2013.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Nellie | last=Andreeva | title=Torrance Coombs To Co-Star in CW Pilot 'Reign', Thomas McDonell Joins 'The 100', Lane Garrison Cast In 'Bonnie & Clyde' Mini | url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/03/torrance-coombs-to-co-star-in-cw-pilot-reign-thomas-mcdonell-joins-the-100-lane-garrison-cast-in-bonnie-clyde-mini/ | website=Deadline Hollywood | date=March 11, 2013|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> Sebastian is an original character created for the show, so Coombs didn't have as much research in preparation for the role, though he faced the challenge of changing his performance from that in ''[[The Tudors]]'', another historical TV series he'd been involved in.<ref>{{ cite web|first=Jenna |last=Busch |title=Reign: Torrance Coombs on The CW's New Historical Drama |url=http://voice.fan.tv/2013/10/14/reign-torrance-coombs-cws-new-historical-drama/ |date=October 14, 2013 |accessdate=February 7, 2014 |work=Fan TV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221214949/http://voice.fan.tv/2013/10/14/reign-torrance-coombs-cws-new-historical-drama/ |archivedate=February 21, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | first=Morgan | last=Glennan | title='Reign' Interview: Toby Regbo and Torrance Coombs Discuss The Royal Love Triangle | url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/reign/reign-interview-toby-regbo-and-51640.aspx | date=October 24, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2014 | work=BuddyTV | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222210150/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/reign/reign-interview-toby-regbo-and-51640.aspx# | archive-date=February 22, 2014 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Alan Van Sprang, who was cast as Henry II of France, modeled his performance after [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=\"huffingtonca\">{{ cite web | first=Denette| last=Wilford| title='Reign' Cast Gets Down And Dirty With Details on Royal TV Show | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/10/16/reign-cw-tv-show-cast-review_n_4101541.html | date=October 16, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2014 | work=The Huffington Post }}</ref> In November 2013, [[Amy Brenneman]] was announced as having been cast as Mary Stuart's mother, [[Mary de Guise]], a role that initially went to Brenneman's ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'' co-star [[Kate Walsh (actress)|Kate Walsh]], who was unable to commit due to conflicting filming commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/amy-brenneman-reign-1200887355/ |title=Amy Brenneman Joins CW's 'Reign' |work=Variety |date=November 26, 2013 |accessdate=December 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | first=Tierney | last=Bricker | title=Surprise! Kate Walsh Was Supposed to Play the Mom on This Amazing CW Show&nbsp;... |url= http://www.eonline.com/news/507742/surprise-kate-walsh-was-supposed-to-play-the-mom-on-this-amazing-cw-show- | date=February 5, 2014 | accessdate=February 7, 2014 }}</ref> On March 10, 2015, it was announced that [[Rachel Skarsten]] has been cast as [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]], a role that debuted in finale of season two and become a regular in season three.<ref name=\"casting1\">{{ cite web | first=Lesley | last=Goldberg | title=CW's 'Reign' Finds Its Queen Elizabeth in 'Fifty Shades of Grey' Alum | date=March 10, 2015 | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/cws-reign-finds-queen-elizabeth-780362 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref> Showrunner McCarthy described the addition of Elizabeth as expanding the scope of the series, and that she will be part of season three's focus on the show's three queens.<ref name=\"casting1\" />\n\n===Filming===\nA large part of the filming for the first season took place in [[Toronto]] and the Republic of Ireland. The third and fourth seasons were also largely filmed in Toronto. [[Rockwood Conservation Area]] near [[Guelph]], Ontario and [[Parkwood Estate]] in [[Oshawa]], Ontario have also been used to mimic 16th-century Scotland for the show's production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/11/17/reign-filming-at-the-parkwood-estate-in-ontario/|title='Reign' filming at the Parkwood Estate in Ontario  - On Location Vacations|date=November 17, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonca\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cw-reign-canadas-whizbang-films-565358|title=Canada's Whizbang Films and Take 5 Productions to Co-Produce CW's 'Reign'|publisher=|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bellmediapr.ca/Network/MuchMore/Press/All-Hail-The-Queen-M3-Premieres-Exclusive-Racy-Period-Drama-REIGN-Oct-16-|title=Press Releases \u2013 Bell Media|website=www.bellmediapr.ca|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMost of the other interior scenes, including bedchambers, the Great Hall, and the Throne Room, were filmed in vast sets primarily at [[Cinespace Film Studios]]' [[Kipling Avenue]] facility.\n\n===Editing for sexual content===\nThe show's pilot was distributed on May 20, 2013, to advertisers and critics for promotion and to generate hype.<ref>{{ cite web|last=Kaye|first=Dierdre|title=The CW makes it Reign|url=http://www.sheknows.com/entertainment/articles/994257/the-cws-new-show-reign|publisher=She Knows Entertainment|date=May 20, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013 }}</ref> The pilot was edited before its final airing on October 13, trimming the sexual content of the scene where Kenna masturbates after witnessing a bedding ceremony.<ref>{{ cite web | first=James | last=Hibberd | title=The CW trims 'Reign' masturbation scene | url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/10/14/reign-masturbation-scene/ | date=October 14, 2013 | accessdate=January 29, 2014 | publisher=InsideTV.com }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | first=Brian | last=Steinberg | title=Sex on Broadcast TV Needs Plot: Networks that use intimacy merely to titillate are stripping themselves of integrity | url=https://variety.com/2013/biz/news/cw-pushes-limits-of-sex-on-network-tv-with-reign-1200710355/ | date=October 11, 2013 | accessdate=January 29, 2014 | work=Variety }}</ref> A later episode of the season, 1.13 \"The Consummation\", has two versions: an on-air cut for television broadcast, and an online streaming version with additional sexual content that was made available on the CW's website a few hours later.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Nikara | last=Johns | title=CW's 'Reign' Streams Racy Episode for a Network TV First | date=March 7, 2014 | accessdate=March 8, 2014 | url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/cws-reign-streams-racy-episode-for-a-network-tv-first-1201127893/ | work=Variety }}</ref> This action was criticized by the [[Parents Television Council]] for putting sexual content online \"where presumably children will be able to watch them with no rating or blocking capability\".<ref>{{ cite web | first=Don | last=Kaplan | title=The CW puts a racier version of a 'Reign' episode online, and the Parents Television Council is fuming | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/racier-reign-episode-incenses-watchdog-group-article-1.1714387 | date=March 9, 2014 | accessdate=March 10, 2014 | publisher=NYDaily.com }}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasts==\n''Reign'' was announced on The CW's 2013 autumn line-up on May 10, 2013, placing it in the Thursday timeslot following ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]'', its biggest hit in young women demographic.<ref name=\"ewanounce\" /> The show had its series premiere on October 17, 2013, in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/07/29/the-cw-moves-up-the-originals-premiere-to-follow-the-vampire-diaries-supernatural-gets-earlier-start/194519/ |title=The CW Moves Up 'The Originals' Premiere to Follow 'The Vampire Diaries' + 'Supernatural' Gets Earlier Start|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=July 29, 2013|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> In Canada, the series airs a day earlier on [[M3 (Canadian TV channel)|M3]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bellmediapr.ca/Network/MuchMore/Press/All-Hail-The-Queen-M3-Premieres-Exclusive-Racy-Period-Drama-REIGN-Oct-16-|title=All Hail The Queen! M3 Premieres Exclusive, Racy, Period Drama REIGN, Oct 16|publisher=Bell Media Press Room|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> in simulcast with The CW on [[CTV Two]], and in reruns on [[E! (Canadian TV channel)|E! Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/Reign.aspx|title=Reign on CTV<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref> Beginning with season three, the show move to the latter network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yuhndDuvAeQ|title=Reign - Season 3 Premiere- E!|first=|last=EonlineCanada|date=September 22, 2015|publisher=|accessdate=March 18, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn New Zealand, [[Prime (New Zealand)|Prime]] premiered the show Thursdays at 9:30&nbsp;pm, starting November 21, 2013. In Australia, ''Reign'' was originally scheduled to premiere on [[Eleven (TV channel)|Eleven]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/11/ten-upfronts-sport-kylie-kwong-and-6pm-entertainment.html|title=TEN Upfronts: Sport, Kylie Kwong, and 6pm entertainment|last=Knox|first=David|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref> but premiered on [[Fox8]] on August 5, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2014/07/airdate-reign.html|title=Airdate: Reign|last=Knox|first=David|publisher=TV Tonight|date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2014}}</ref> In Ireland the show broadcasts in the early mornings on [[RT\u00c92]] each Thursday at 02:15.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/listings_rtetwo.html|title=TV Guide - Listings For All Irish Television Channels - RT\u00c9|publisher=|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref> The first two seasons of ''Reign'' are available for online streaming on [[Netflix]] in the UK and Ireland. New episodes from Season 3 onwards are uploaded weekly to Netflix in the United Kingdom as the exclusive broadcaster hours after they air in the US, but not Ireland where they are exclusive to RT\u00c9 until the season finishes airing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Netflix Picks Up UK Rights To 'Reign' Season 3 - TVWise|url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2015/10/netflix-picks-up-uk-rights-to-reign-season-3/|website=TVWise|language=en-US|date=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAll four seasons are available for streaming on Netflix in the U.S. and the Middle East, and a great part of Europe.\n\n==Reception==\nResponse to the show was mixed, with various critics highlighting the show's focus on romance and teenage drama instead of historical accuracy. A number of reviewers compared it to ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', with similar emphasis on fashion, drama, and soap opera antics.<ref name=\"avclubchosen\">{{ cite web| last=Valentine|first=Genevieve|title=Reign: \"Chosen\"|url=https://www.avclub.com/review/chosen-105817|publisher=A.V. Club|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"miamiherald\">{{ cite web|last=Garvin|first=Glenn|title=Think of CW's 'Reign' as 'Mary, Teen of Scots'|work=The Miami Herald|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/10/16/3691455/think-of-cws-reign-as-mary-teen.html|date=October 16, 2013|accessdate=November 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday\">{{ cite web|first=Bianco|last=Robert|title=Wrong as 'Reign': CW ignores history, insults viewers|work=USA Today|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/10/16/reign-review/2994343/|date=October 16, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"communityvoice\">{{ cite web|first=Rob|last=Owen|title=There will be no reining in of 'Reign'|url=http://communityvoices.post-gazette.com/arts-entertainment-living/tuned-in/item/37487-there-will-be-no-reining-in-of-reign|date=November 14, 2013|publisher=Community Voices|accessdate=December 9, 2013 }}</ref> The review of the pilot by ''[[The New York Times]]'' described ''Reign'' a strong candidate as a \"camp classic\", calling it fun and acknowledging its historical inaccuracies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hale|first=Mike|title=Even a Doomed Queen Just Wants to Have Fun|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/arts/television/cws-reign-depicts-mary-queen-of-scots-as-a-teenager.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 16, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> The reviewer of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' described the show as more \"an alternate-universe fanfiction than anything pretending to approach history\", calling the show camp and fun.<ref name=\"avclubchosen\" /> ''[[The Miami Herald]]'' described the show's opening episodes as \"surprisingly entertaining\", with Adelaide Kane's portrayal of Mary as \"a teenager with a dawning realization that her royal caprices can have unexpectedly grim consequences offers an interesting take on the traditional coming-of-age story\".<ref name=\"miamiherald\"/> The review of Flavorwire described the show as \"fantastical princess wish-fulfilment\", a guilty pleasure that is relaxing to watch, and that its historical inaccuracy is to its advantage: \"There is something about abandoning all pretense of authenticity that gives this story a lightness it badly needs; dead-seriousness just isn't something that plays all that well at the moment.\"<ref>{{ cite web | first=Michelle | last=Dean | title=The CW's 'Reign' Is the Guilty-Pleasure Period Drama You've Been Waiting For | url=http://flavorwire.com/420582/the-cws-reign-is-the-guilty-pleasure-period-drama-youve-been-waiting-for/ | date=October 17, 2013 | accessdate=February 7, 2014 }}</ref> ''Community Voices'' highlighted ''Reign'' as an interesting departure from The CW's other shows, but described it as stuck in a rut, making it difficult to sustain a show that's \"built on a binary premise: either Mary and Francis are coming together or they are drifting apart.\"<ref name=\"communityvoice\" /> A review by a ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' critic was more critical, saying that the \"sexed-up version of high school with horses\" show \"does not deserve\" its main character, who is described as a \"''[[The Princess Diaries]]'' knock-off\", but acknowledged that the show is self-aware of its position as a guilty pleasure.<ref>{{ cite web|last=McNamara|first=Mary|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/oct/17/entertainment/la-et-st-reign-review-cw-20131017|title=Review: The CW's 'Reign' sexes up, dumbs down Mary, Queen of Scots|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 17, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' is also critical, describing the show as anachronistic and \"dumbing down\" history for the sake of entertainment.<ref name=\"usatoday\" />\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n! {{Abbr|Refs|References}}\n\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|2014\n|[[Hollywood Post Alliance|Hollywood Post Alliance Awards]]\n|Outstanding Color Grading \u2013 Television\n|\"Pilot\"<br />David Cole \u2013 Modern VideoFilm\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://hollywoodpostalliance.org/?p=31041|title=2014 Hollywood Post Alliance Award Winners Announced|work=Hollywood Post Alliance|accessdate=December 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|The Joey Awards\n|Young Actress age 9 or younger in a TV Series Drama or Comedy Guest Starring or Principal Role\n|Vanessa Carter\n|{{nominated}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.joeyawards.com/2014nominations.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028053006/http://www.joeyawards.com/2014nominations.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 28, 2014 |title=2014 NOMINATIONS & WINNERS |website=Joeyawards.com |accessdate=December 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice Breakout Series|Choice TV: Breakout Show]]\n|''Reign''\n|{{nominated}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Teen Choice 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/07/17/second-wave-of-nominations-for-teen-choice-2014-announced/283935/ |title=Second Wave of Nominations for 'Teen Choice 2014' Announced |date=July 18, 2014 |work=[[TV by the Numbers]] |accessdate=July 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928084947/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/07/17/second-wave-of-nominations-for-teen-choice-2014-announced/283935/ |archivedate=September 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Choice TV: Female Breakout Star\n|Adelaide Kane\n|{{nominated}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Teen Choice 2014\" />\n|-\n|Choice TV: Male Breakout Star\n|Toby Regbo\n|{{nominated}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"Teen Choice 2014\" />\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Monte-Carlo Television Festival]]\n|Outstanding Actor in a Drama Series\n|Torrance Coombs\n|{{nominated}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n|Outstanding Actress in a Drama Series\n|Adelaide Kane\n|{{nominated}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n|[[People's Choice Awards]]\n|Favorite New TV Drama\n|''Reign''\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- Staff report --> |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2014/01/08/peo